Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Sentencing hearing on December 19, 2022 at 09:15 am.
Sentencing hearing on November 14, 2022 at 01:45 pm.
Order for PSI and Criminal complaint sent to DOC interface 10/21/22

9:00 AM Court calls cases: 21CF110, 22CF48 and DA Kelz states appearances. Defendant Dayna Catherine Lemmer in court.  Attorney Brian Christopher Williams in court for Dayna Catherine Lemmer.  Attorney Karl J. Kelz in court for State of Wisconsin. DA Kelz gives a status update in the case and recites the prliminary agreement. DA Kelz requests a PSI in each case. Attorney Williams concurs. Court orders a PSI be ordered for both cases. Attorney Williams makes comments in regards to the agreement. DA Kelz clarifies the terms. Court questions parties on a sentencing date. DA Kelz states the PSI could take roughly 6 weeks to complete so a sentencing date will be set with the judicial assistant off record. Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST to the sole counts in cases 21CF110 and  22CF48. Court questions DE regarding the plea. DA explains elements of charge.  Court finds plea/waiver to be free, etc.  Court finds factual basis does exist.  Court accepts plea, finds DE guilty and orders a Presentence Investigation be ordered.
Plea hearing on October 12, 2022 at 09:00 am.

10:45 AM DA calls cases 21CF110 and 22CF48 and states appearances. Defendant Dayna Catherine Lemmer appeared with attorney Brian Christopher Williams via zoom technologies.  Karl J. Kelz appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Attorney Williams states his client will be waiving the preliminary hearing in each case. Court questions Attorney Williams on waiver form. Attorney Williams gives responses. Court in recess at 10:49 am to allow defendant to reconnect to zoom due to bad conection. Clerk calls defendant to appear by phone/ audio due to faulty connection on zoom. Back on record at 10:52 AM. Defendant questions defendant in regards to waiver.   Preliminary Hearing waived by the defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently.  Waiver accepted by the Court.   Court finds probable cause exists that a crime was committed and binds DE over for trial.  Information filed, acknowledged by parties and reading waived.   DE enters plea of NOT GUILTY to all counts in each case. Victim Rights Legislations have been complied with.
Preliminary hearing on May 23, 2022 at 10:30 am.

If not already completed DE must submit to booking at Sheriff's Dept prior to release.
Defendant shall give written notice prior to any change in address or telephone number to the Clerk of this Court and Defense Attorney.Defendant may not have contact with the Park Falls Chamber of Commerce or any board member unless a written waiver is filed with the Clerk of Courts Office OR the Price County Sheriff's Office outside of business hours

10:03 AM Defendant Dayna Catherine Lemmer appeared with attorney Brian Christopher Williams.  Karl J. Kelz appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Complaint acknowledged, reading waived.   Preliminary hearing requested, time limits waived.  Court orders Pre-trial conference be scheduled.
